topian philosopher Tommaso Campanella, which, as if by enchantment, transport them back four centuries to Naples. And while the past and present miraculously converge, Leyla, Michael, and Tommaso embark on a voyage of self-discovery in search of a new life. In this fusion of historical, queer, and speculative fiction, Alessandro Giardino combines the intellectual playfulness of Umberto Eco with the psychological finesse of Michael Cunningham.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aliterature, fiction, italian, italy, translation, art, pop culture, lgbt, drama, relationship, Tommaso Campanella, The Seven Works of Mercy, naples, paris, new york.1 aGiardino, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerjian, Ara H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMerjian, Ara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMyerson, Joyce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197883952640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978839526423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978839526/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles